metadata.name: Galdricge #28
metadata.description:
Galdricge, meaning 'Enchantress' in Anglo-Saxon, is an attempt to evoke a sense of grace and femininity from stark, abstract elements. 


Add "&png" to querystring for 2048x2048 png export 
Add "&svg" for svg export. There are up to 5 layers which can be controlled in Inkscape for different pen widths and colours 


This work is plottable thanks to open-sourced code and article from twilliability. Check out his plotter pieces at https://www.fxhash.xyz/u/twilliability  
Article : https://jealousmarkup.xyz/texts/webgl-line-hiding 
Code : https://gist.github.com/gugray/dfdbef073a3efe1abb5f501728ac9d51 


Other libs (refer console output for license info) 
Graphics : PIXIJS https://github.com/pixijs/pixijs 
Geometry : JSTS https://github.com/bjornharrtell/jsts 
Noise : SIMPLEX-NOISE https://github.com/jwagner/simplex-noise.js 
Random number lib : Fdrandom.js https://github.com/strainer/fdrandom.js 


Made on and off, over 5 months of the great 2023 bear market.

metadata.name: Special Token [RESERVE PASS] #29
metadata.description:
Back when I was a researcher at a human-computer interaction lab, I parked in the adjacent neighborhood and rode the city bus into campus.

Usually this was a pretty uneventful affair.

One spring day though, the bus was packed and I had to stand right up front by the driver. Despite trying to appear busy enough not to be bothered, the driver struck up a conversation.

At some point in the short trip, we stopped at a red light. It was then that he made an off-hand comment that I've remembered ever since.

‚ÄúThe moment between when the light turns green and when I realize it, that‚Äôs where my soul resides.‚Äù

I‚Äôm not sure how you‚Äôre supposed to respond to that. But nevertheless it smacked me.

So: do not consider each of these my personal signature as an artist, developer, and tinkerer.

Do consider them an expended shard of my soul and the culmination of experiences that have led up to this moment.

This is the light turning green.

---

THIS TOKEN IS A RESERVE PASS (it‚Äôs ‚ú®special‚ú®)

- This token will function as a reserve pass for any future drop on fx(hash) that has a total edition size of > 100 (ie, most of my drops, other than dedicated ‚Äúsketch‚Äù projects that may have intentionally fewer editions)

- Future reserves will be limited to holders of this token, and holding this token will guarantee you a dedicated 24 hour reserve spot on such projects.

- Holding any token from my prior projects will make you eligible to mint from this drop (I will take a final snapshot ~1 hr prior to drop).

- I have created an edition size of 60, but only 40 will be open for minting at this time. I‚Äôll reserve the remainder for issuing or burning at my discretion.

- I will also airdrop ~9 editions to the top collectors of my previous projects (consider Twitter to be the source of info on this prior to the drop)

WHY?

I don‚Äôt like the idea of picking and choosing who gets a reserve and who doesn‚Äôt.

I love you all üôè

---

- Made with p5JS
- Press ‚Äús‚Äù to save png

metadata.name: Intangible #171
metadata.description:
Let me take you places. Those are not in your town, not even on your planet. They‚Äôre placed somewhere between reality and subconsciousness.
Enormous, peculiar structures emerge upon you, refusing to be ignored. They are your unfulfilled cravings or ever-lurking demons. They were always there, under your skin, intangible, now they‚Äôve materialized.
You may not like them, they may seem too vast, too scary to tame. But ultimately, you have to face them, unless you enjoy living in their shadow.¬†

___
Inspirations

I‚Äôve never truly realized that, but ever since I remember, the sight of gigantic objects or creatures evoked strong emotions within me.
It probably started with playing Shadow of Colossus (a video game) as a kid and seeing The Cathedral (short movie by Tomasz Bagi≈Ñski). Years later, reading Solaris (by Stanis≈Çaw Lem) aroused the same feeling (among others) of being mesmerized by the vastness. More recently, movies like Denis Villeneuve‚Äôs Arrival (which also nudged my attraction to mystery) and Dune - have charmed me.

Earlier this year I have stumbled across Dawid Planeta (artist and yoga teacher) and began contemplating his visions of mini people in the jungle inhabited by giant animals. These works in particular, plus Hollow - generative series by Jacek Markusiewicz - were probably my final inspirations to make Intangible look the way it does.

Settling semi-random generative structures in some kind of reality, gave them a meaning - they may symbolize things much bigger than you - the ones you try to escape from or those you‚Äôve been longing to experience for years. I have mine, don‚Äôt you?

___
Controls in live mode


Keyboard
[ space ] - toggle light animation
[ S ] - save image with current size (default is 120% of browser window‚Äôs height; you may change browser‚Äôs scale or check URL size param)
[ F ] - fullscreen¬†
[ up / down ] - light intensity
[ left / right ] - base light position
[ 1..5 ] - aspect ratio: 10:16 (‚Äûzero‚Äù ratio), 1:1.4142 (vertical A4), 1:1, 1.4142 (horizontal A4), 16:10
[ B ] - toggle border
[ Z ] - toggle canvas ‚Äûraw‚Äù mode - no shadow / margin (auto applied in fullscreen mode)
[ N ] - toggle ‚Äûthat thing you may not want on print‚Äù


URL params
You may add any number of parameters to the URL to start it with particular settings.‚Ä®
[ animate ] (1/0) - toggle light animation
[ size] (number) - number of px for longer edge, i.e. 4000
[ ratio ] (number or ratio with format: 10/16, 10:16, 10_16) - aspect ratio
[ light ] (number 40..120, some palettes have slightly different limits for good results) - light intensity
[ lightShift] (number -100..100) - base light position
[ border ] (1/0) - toggle border
[ hddcy ] (0/1)

Example: [ &size=4000&border=1&light=100&animate=1 ]¬†


Mobile
[hold 2 fingers for 2s] - save
[double tap] - fullscreen


___
Note:
I encourage you to do some light adjustments before you save an image for print. I‚Äôm pretty sure you can do better than fxrand().


___
Special thanks to my brother Krzycho, for lots of advices / heathy criticism and to Olga, for never-ending excitement and ‚Äûdorady‚Äù.

___
Developed in Javascript, using p5.js (2D Canvas) and chroma.js.

metadata.name: mezcal #305
metadata.description:
a reflection/meditation on the idea that over time, we hold certain memories as perfect moments in time. they are not still like a photograph. they flow like a river, searching and branching out into the fractal of our existence.
over time they can become something completely different. but if the memory is all that's left. then what was ever true to begin with ?

--------------------------

press 's' to save png to device. artwork resolution regenerates according to window size.

to create a higher resolution image: zoom out as much as possible, then hit refresh.
tested with chrome.

metadata.name: Morphing Convictions #45
metadata.description:
Everyday we move on by relying on our convictions. Their immutability often helps us take decisions or take shelter but can sometimes clash with the unknown, the different and the new. They can then crack, crumble and mutate. To change your convictions means changing the kind of person you want to be. It means changing your self-identity. And that is not just hard, it is scary. And beautiful.

Morphing Convictions is a piece that exists through two kind of outputs : Posters and Scenes. Posters are focusing on the contemplation of details and movements of a morphing conviction while the Scenes are interactive little worlds where you can explore a conviction in it's environment.

Please open in live mode to enjoy a much better experience.

Controls :

Posters & Scenes
‚Ä¢ Click anywhere to enable audio.
‚Ä¢ Press M to toggle mute.
‚Ä¢ Press F to toggle the fullscreen mode.
‚Ä¢ Press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to make a capture and download a PNG with a resolution of x1, x2, x3 or x4.

Scenes only
‚Ä¢ Drag and scroll to rotate and zoom.
‚Ä¢ Click on objects, some might react.

‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî

Morphing Convictions by Ferdinand Dervieux, 2022
Made with Unity

metadata.name: Vertical World #107
metadata.description:
This artwork is a kind of my inquiry about ambiguous boundaries.
I was a child who liked to draw but always been dissatisfied with my work. Now through coding, I was able to create the "feelings" that I wanted to express. This work is not to imitate a certain landscape or painting style, but simply paint with different brushes, and cooperate with the randomness of the computer.
"I" creates horizontal order, and "computer" creates vertical disorder. My intention is to create
ambiguous visuals in a way that doesn't give specific images, but vague atmosphere.
The meaning is computer-generated and positioned through your eyes.
(It may take more time to render if you using Firefox browser.)

- Press [s] to save png image

Created by haxenfan using p5js.
